<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-10-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-10-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="787" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d787">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Day</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-10-04"><hi rend="italic">October 4,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 2.]</seg></opener>
                        <p>The opinions of Admiral Dewey, in the possession of the commission, seem
                            to favor retention of Luzon alone, but appear to have been given in
                            answer to question as to which island in Philippine Islands the United
                            States should retain. If this assumption is correct will you, if it is
                            deemed advisable, ascertain by telegraph through proper channel, and
                            telegraph us whether Admiral has formed an opinion and, if so, what it
                            is on the question whether it would be better for United States to
                            retain Luzon and perhaps one or two small adjacent islands or the whole
                            group?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Day.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>